div.p: The paging algorithm takes care of converting a search intention into a page layout which can be consumed by the Search Executor to call the Client Driver accordingly. This diagram provides visual examples of use cases.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; overflow: hidden; max-height: 95px; max-width: 290px; width: 290px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal;

div.p: A common example for a limited search can be framed as "get me the first five entities".

switch.text:
Limited Search

A common example for a limited search can be framed as "get me the first five entities".

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 92px; white-space: nowrap; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;

div.p: A common example for a limitless search can be framed as "get me the all entities which are available".

div.p: This search variant just skips the first n entities, while fetching the results until nothing is left. So it is not limited. (visual example is not optimized)

div.p: While skipping the first n entities, we want to limit the result set to m entities. The actual result set may be less than m when the data store just does not have as much data available.

div.p: When a single page fits the limits of the API and the user search and no offset is required, the page boundaries are aligned. This means that the full page contents are used. No slicing is required.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; overflow: hidden; max-height: 138px; max-width: 315px; width: 315px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal;

div.p: Even multiple pages may be fully aligned to their boundaries when the search intention and the API limits fit together. A search offset may be defined as well, but needs to serve the requirements to keep the page layout fully aligned.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 39px; white-space: nowrap; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;

div.p: When a single page fits the limits of the API and the user search and no offset is required, the page boundaries are aligned. This means that the full page contents are used. No slicing is required.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; overflow: hidden; max-height: 163px; max-width: 315px; width: 315px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal;

div.p: While optimizing for the least requests to perform on the Client Driver level and the maximum content per page, the page layout may request full pages while slicing its start or end to fit the search intention. So elements are transmitted but removed on the client side.

div.style: display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; width: 39px; white-space: nowrap; overflow-wrap: normal; text-align: center;

display: inline-block; font-size: 12px; font-family: Helvetica; color: rgb(0, 0, 0); line-height: 1.2; vertical-align: top; overflow: hidden; max-height: 158px; max-width: 315px; width: 315px; white-space: normal; overflow-wrap: normal;

div.p: Search intentions may contain an offset or not. Depending on the offset the first page to fetch can be fully boundary aligned. The same affects search intention limits. When the limit is odd so the last page boundary is unaligned, the contents must be sliced.

div.p: The worst case for the page layout is the presence of a user intension offset and limit which results in unaligned boundaries on the first and last page. Then the result set must be sliced on both ends to fit the user request.
